{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488866"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:00:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"563"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/563"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.08,0.77,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"563","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/563"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"563"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"163"},{"type":"tags","id":"1036"},{"type":"tags","id":"2074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2602"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31690"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40966"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42099"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing shortness of breath on exertion. He has a medical history of untreated hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia and gout. He smokes 20 cigarettes per day and drinks four to five standard drinks of alcohol daily. He does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears mildly short of breath. His pulse rate is 86/min, blood pressure 154/82 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Bibasal crackles are heard on chest auscultation. His heart sounds are dual with an S3. His jugular venous pressure is elevated at 4 cm with a prominent a wave.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to determine the underlying cause of this patients presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Computed tomography pulmonary angiogram","Chest X-ray","Echocardiogram","Electrocardiogram","N-terminal pro B-type natriuretic peptide"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical features highly suggestive of congestive heart failure, including exertional dyspnoea, bibasal crackles, elevated jugular venous pressure, and an S3 heart sound. He also has multiple risk factors including untreated hypertension, smoking, and excessive alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial investigation as it provides both diagnostic clarity and prognostic information. It can assess systolic and diastolic function, identify structural abnormalities, and evaluate valve function. It is considered the gold standard investigation for heart failure as it can determine both the type and severity of cardiac dysfunction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if pulmonary embolism was suspected. However, the chronic nature of symptoms and presence of typical heart failure signs make this diagnosis less likely. CT pulmonary angiogram also carries risks of contrast nephropathy and radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChest X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E can show features of heart failure such as pulmonary oedema, pleural effusions, and increased cardiothoracic ratio. While useful as an initial screening tool, it cannot provide detailed information about cardiac function or the underlying cause of heart failure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElectrocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is important in the assessment of heart failure as it may show evidence of previous myocardial infarction, left ventricular hypertrophy, or arrhythmias. However, it cannot provide direct information about cardiac function or structural abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-terminal pro B-type natriuretic peptide\u003C/strong\u003E is a useful biomarker for heart failure, particularly for ruling out the diagnosis when levels are normal. However, in a patient with clear clinical signs of heart failure, echocardiography provides more comprehensive diagnostic and prognostic information.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Echocardiogram is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing heart failure as it provides both diagnostic and prognostic information.","Clinical features of heart failure include exertional dyspnoea, bibasal crackles, elevated JVP, and presence of S3.","Risk factors for heart failure include hypertension, smoking, and excessive alcohol consumption."],"references":["NHFA CSANZ Heart failure guidelines working group. National Heart Foundation of Australia and Cardiac Society of Australia and New Zealand: Guidelines for the Prevention, Detection, and Management of Heart Failure in Australia 2018. Heart, Lung and Circulation. 2018; 27: 1123-1208."]},"relationships":{"itemRevisi